In article <1993Aug16.091602.20500@zh014.ubs.ubs.ch>, zhmhd@zh014.ubs.ubs.ch (Mihailescu Preda) writes:
> 
> There are persistent rumors claiming that the Diffie Hellman scheme
> used by secure rpc would have broken. Even in this newsgroup there has
> once been a claim, that in 1988 or 1989 such an attack would have
> succeeded. I have however not seen any reply to this claim, nor was it
> backed up by some verifiable reference.  I know that secure rpc uses a
> 192 bits prime p of the shape 2*q+1, where q is also a prime. So the
> group in which it encrypts has index roughly 2^191 and to the best of
> my knowledge, an attack should succeed to take discrete logarithms in
> this group - which, again, would require at the state of the art in
> discrete logarithms, roughly 2^95 bit operations. This cannot be done!
> It is thus hard to believe this rumour.

This is not a rumor, it's a published paper...  See

@article{nfscrack,
   author = {Brian A. LaMacchia and Andrew M. Odlyzko},
   journal = {Designs, Codes, and Cryptography},
   pages = {46--62},
   title = {Computation of Discrete Logarithms in Prime Fields},
   volume = {1},
   year = {1991},
}


